The '''Creative Problem Solving Process''' (CPS), also known as the Osborn-Parnes CPS process, was developed by Alex Osborn and Dr. Sidney J. Parnes in the 1950s.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://creativeproblemsolving.com/ |title=Creative Problem Solving: Resources for CPS Practitioners |accessdate=2010-06-08 |publisher=OmniSkills, LLC }}</ref> CPS is a structured method for generating novel and useful solutions to problems. CPS follows three process stages, which match a person's natural creative process, and six explicit steps:<ref>[http://www.creativeeducationfoundation.org/?page_id=41 What is CPS?]. Creative Education Foundation, 2010. Retrieved on 2010-06-13.</ref> {| class="wikitable" |- ! Process Stage !! Steps |- | rowspan="3" | Explore the Challenge || Objective Finding (identify the goal, wish or challenge) |- | Fact Finding (gather the relevant data) |- | Problem Finding (clarify the problems that need to be solved in order to achieve the goal) |- | Generate Ideas || Idea Finding (generate ideas to solve the identified problem) |- | rowspan="2" | Prepare for Action || Solution Finding (move from idea to implementable solution) |- | Acceptance Finding (plan for action) |}
CPS is flexible, and its use depends on the situation. The steps can be (and often are) used in a linear fashion, from start to finish, but it is not necessary to use all the steps. For example, if one already has a clearly-defined problem, the process would begin at Idea Finding.
What distinguishes the Osborn-Parnes CPS process from other "creative problem solving" methods is the use of both divergent and convergent thinking during each process step, and not just when generating ideas to solve the problem. Each step begins with divergent thinking, a broad search for many alternatives. This is followed by convergent thinking, the process of evaluating and selecting.
This method is taught at the International Center for Studies in Creativity,<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.buffalostate.edu/creativity/graduatecourses.xml |title=ICSC Course Descriptions |accessdate=2007-12-22 |publisher=International Center for Studies in Creativity }}</ref> the Creative Problem Solving Institute,<ref> {{cite web|url=http://cpsiconference.com/ |title=Creative Problem Solving Institute |accessdate=2007-12-22 |publisher=Creative Education Foundation }}</ref> and CREA Conference.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.creaconference.com/EN/core-programs.html |title=Programs |accessdate=2008-01-07 |work=CREA Conference |publisher=Creativity European Association }}</ref> It is specifically acknowledged as a key influence for the Productive Thinking Model.<ref>{{cite book | last = Hurson | first = Tim | coauthors = | title = Think Better: An Innovator's Guide to Productive Thinking | publisher = McGraw Hill | year = 2007 | location = New York, New York | pages = xii | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0071494939 }}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
{{BookCat}}

'''6-3-5 Brainwriting ''' (also known as the 6-3-5 Method, or Method 635) is a group creativity technique used in marketing, advertising, design, writing and product development originally developed by Professor Bernd Rohrbach in 1968<ref>''Rohrbach, Bernd'': "Kreativ nach Regeln – Methode 635, eine neue Technik zum Lösen von Problemen". ''Creative by rules - Method 635, a new technique for solving problems'' first published in the German sales magazine "Absatzwirtschaft", Volume 12, 1969. p73-75 and Volume 19, 1 October 1969.</ref>.

Based on the concept of [[../Brainstorming/]], the aim of 6-3-5 Brainwriting is to generate 108 new ideas in half an hour. In a similar way to brainstorming, it is not the quality of ideas that matters but the quantity.

The technique involves 6 participants who sit in a group and are supervised by a moderator. Each participant thinks up 3 ideas every 5 minutes. Participants are encouraged to draw on others' ideas for inspiration, thus stimulating the creative process. After 6 rounds in 30 minutes the group has thought up a total of 108 ideas.

